Probably better sent to <#C2YH119N2|hubl>. But yes, this is possible, You could simply do a check on the `loop.index` like
```  &lt;div class="row"&gt;
    {% for %}
      {% if loop.index &lt;= 10 %}

      {% endif %}
    {% endfor %}
  &lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div class="row"&gt;
    {% for %}
      {% if loop.index &gt; 10 &amp;&amp; loop.index &lt;= 20 %}

      {% endif %}
    {% endfor %}
  &lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div class="row"&gt;
    {% for %}
      {% if loop.index &gt; 20 &amp;&amp; loop.index &lt;= 30 %}

      {% endif %}
    {% endfor %}
  &lt;/div&gt;```
Pretty bad way to do it, could be more dynamic, modular, and DRY, but should work for your example, if thatâ€™s all you want to do.

A better way would probably be like:
```{% set items_per_row = 10 %}
{% for x in y %}
  {% if loop.index % items_per_row == 0 || loop.first %}
    {% set base = (loop.index / items_per_row)|round(0, 'floor') * items_per_row %}
    &lt;div class="row"&gt;
      {% for x in y %}
        {% if loop.index &gt; base &amp;&amp; loop.index &lt;= base + items_per_row %}

        {% endif %}
      {% endfor %}
    &lt;/div&gt;
  {% endif %}
{% endfor %}```
